Linux Forensics 

⸻

1. OS & System Identification

Command

cat /etc/os-release

Path

/etc/os-release

What it gives
	•	OS name
	•	Version
	•	Distribution type

Why it matters
	•	Determines:
	•	Log locations
	•	Package manager
	•	Known vulnerabilities

⸻

2. Hostname

Command

cat /etc/hostname

Path

/etc/hostname

Purpose
	•	Identifies system in network/logs

⸻

3. Timezone

Command

cat /etc/timezone

Path

/etc/timezone

Why important
	•	Needed for timeline correlation
	•	Prevents misinterpretation of logs

⸻

4. User Enumeration

Command

cat /etc/passwd
cat /etc/passwd | column -t -s :

Path

/etc/passwd

Structure

username : x : UID : GID : comment : home : shell

Key Points
	•	UID 0 → root
	•	UID ≥ 1000 → normal users
	•	/bin/bash → login allowed
	•	/usr/sbin/nologin → no login

⸻

5. Password Storage

Path

/etc/shadow

Meaning
	•	Stores hashed passwords
	•	/etc/passwd shows x → password stored here

⸻

6. Group Enumeration

Command

cat /etc/group

Path

/etc/group

Structure

group : x : GID : users

Important Groups
	•	sudo → root access
	•	adm → log access
	•	root → full control

⸻

Check user groups

id username
groups username


⸻

7. Sudo Privileges

Command

sudo cat /etc/sudoers

Path

/etc/sudoers

Important Lines

root ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL
%sudo ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL

Meaning
	•	%sudo → group-based privilege
	•	Users in sudo group → full root access

⸻

8. Login History

Commands

last
last -f /var/log/wtmp
last -f /var/log/btmp

Paths

/var/log/wtmp   → successful logins
/var/log/btmp   → failed logins

Notes
	•	Binary files → cannot use cat
	•	Use last

⸻

9. Authentication Logs

Command

cat /var/log/auth.log
cat /var/log/auth.log* | grep COMMAND

Path

/var/log/auth.log

What it shows
	•	SSH logins
	•	sudo usage
	•	privilege escalation
	•	user creation

⸻

Example interpretation

COMMAND=/usr/bin/cat /etc/sudoers

→ user executed command as root

⸻

10. Syslog (System Activity)

